         <abstract>
            <p>Our postwar debt may amount to $280 billion, and the annual interest charge to $6 billion. Total federal, state and local government expenditures may run to $29 or $30 billion—about 25% of a $120 billion national income. We can not accept the philosophy that we should go ahead and formulate the ideal program of what government should do, and let expenses care for themselves. It is erroneous to assert that it is generally desirable to have a continuously unbalanced budget and constantly increasing debt. Government credit will fail, and we will have repudiation or inflation. Once government has the freedom that comes from unlimited expenditure of borrowed money, we are headed for totalitarianism. We must set our sights on a postwar balanced budget, and then start paying off the debt.</p>
         </abstract>
